1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,400
This garden waters itself, and the

2
00:00:02,400 --> 00:00:04,800
brain behind it costs seventeen pounds.

3
00:00:04,800 --> 00:00:07,122
Most watering systems run on a

4
00:00:07,122 --> 00:00:09,444
timer. They flood beds after rain

5
00:00:09,444 --> 00:00:11,766
and leave them dry in a

6
00:00:11,766 --> 00:00:14,088
heatwave, because a clock doesn't know

7
00:00:14,088 --> 00:00:16,410
what the soil actually needs.

8
00:00:16,410 --> 00:00:18,490
This one reads the soil instead.

9
00:00:18,490 --> 00:00:20,570
A capacitive moisture sensor sits in

10
00:00:20,570 --> 00:00:22,650
each bed, wired through an analogue-to-digital

11
00:00:22,650 --> 00:00:24,730
board so the Pi can actually

12
00:00:24,730 --> 00:00:26,810
understand it.

13
00:00:26,810 --> 00:00:29,132
Every thirty minutes, the Pi checks

14
00:00:29,132 --> 00:00:31,454
all five beds. Any bed below

15
00:00:31,454 --> 00:00:33,776
its moisture target gets its valve

16
00:00:33,776 --> 00:00:36,098
opened and the pump switched on,

17
00:00:36,098 --> 00:00:38,420
one bed at a time.

18
00:00:38,420 --> 00:00:40,620
It stops the moment the soil

19
00:00:40,620 --> 00:00:42,820
is wet enough, or after a

20
00:00:42,820 --> 00:00:45,020
safety timeout — whichever comes first.

21
00:00:45,020 --> 00:00:47,220
No flooding, no guessing.

22
00:00:47,220 --> 00:00:49,122
The whole thing runs off one

23
00:00:49,122 --> 00:00:51,025
small solar panel, and it won

24
00:00:51,025 --> 00:00:52,927
an engineering award for exactly this

25
00:00:52,927 --> 00:00:54,830
reason.

26
00:00:54,830 --> 00:00:56,563
Full build plans, parts list and

27
00:00:56,563 --> 00:00:58,297
the actual code — link in

28
00:00:58,297 --> 00:01:00,030
bio.
